The Times: -- London's Mayor Ken Livingstone unveiled his controversial
plans to beat traffic congestion in the capital on Tuesday. He announced
that from January 2003, motorists entering the heart of the city will pay a
five pound daily charge or face a series of hefty fines. The Guardian: --
The Tory leadership contest in Britain was thrown wide open Tuesday night
when Michael Portillo won a chaotic first round by a narrow margin than
expected. The Daily Telegraph: -- Tony Blair has set up a powerful crisis
management unit in the cabinet office to deal with national emergencies
following concern about the handling of foot and mouth and the fuel
protest. The Independent: -- Amid signs of increasing restlessness in the
loyalist paramilitary underworld, the British and Irish governments
remained deadlocked in efforts to achieve a breakthrough in the peace
process Tuesday night.
